The strong finding that energy is never created from nothing or removed to nowhere but may change form is widely accepted. However if the issue is reframed as a promise of perpetually mutable free energy it becomes unspeakable. 

It is a direct consequence of energy conservation for refrigerators and air conditioners to export electricity rather than consuming it. 

The elegant way to power our civilization would be to subtract some thermal energy from the planetary ambient by changing its form into electrical energy, use the electrical energy for heat, light, or mechanical energy as we wish and let the heat released by these uses return to the ambient. 

Cell phones wouldn't die or need power cords or batteries or become hot.They would cool when transmiting radio signal power. Frozen food storage would be reliable and free or value positive. That means homes and markets would have independent power to preserve food. Vehicles wouldn't need fuel or fueling stops. Elevators would be very reliable with independent power. Water and sewage pumps may be placed anywhere. With enough progress with the technology H2O and CO2 levels in the biosphere could be modified easily. There should be a unitary agency to look after our planetary concerns. Nomads could manage their material supports item by item and groups of people can modify their settlements with great technical flexibility. 

Will we have a Utopia or Distopia?  

Aloha,
Charles M Brown lll
Kauai, Hawaii

The future is dark, but it has nothing to do with what this video talks about.

Comment: On a certain level, we have Ai in our brain, the neurochemicals that show up in flow: so dopamine, norepinephrine, anandamide, endorphins, and serotonin. If you were to try to cocktail the street drug version of that, right, you're trying to blend like heroin and speed and coke and acid and weed- and point is, you can't do it. It turns out the brain can cocktail all of 'em at once, which is why people will prefer flow to almost any experience on Earth. It's our favorite experience. It's the most addictive experience on Earth. Why? 'Cause it cocktails five or six of the largest pleasure drugs the brain can produce. We're all capable of so much more than we know. That is a commonality across the board. And one of the big reasons is we're all hardwired for flow, and flow is a massive amplification of what's possible for ourselves.

Comment: Something overlooked: those systems process vague input (natural language) for nearly correct (as expected) output. This is the essential key feature in the vast majority of human activities in the service sector. In contexts where perfectly correct answers are not needed, this algorithm can be left to decide on the basis of a non-exhaustive, inconsistent, not entirely correct model of reality, unlike common algorithms. Uncertainty on the inputs and especially on the model for the reality are where the machines stop being effective and the human being is required. This stuff is going to be very invasive.

Comment:
A few questions I have not seen very often about ChatGPT:
How does it learn? Would it be able to watch traffic on the internet, news broadcasts, etc... and be able to synthesize and absorb what it observes?
Given that it is a software program (albeit a very large and complex one) would multiple instances of it, running on different hosts be able to communicate with each other? I'm thinking of the Go playing program that recently beat the world champion. After absorbing historical games played by humans,  it played copies of itself - this resulted in winning strategies not understood by even masters of the game.
What kind of goals would it have?  Humans have basic goals ingrained - to eat, get laid, seek status or power, etc... Does the program have any basic underlying goals to direct its behavior?

Comment:
As a developer who's tried using ChatGPT, it's pretty hit or miss. You can waste a lot of time with it, because it's incredibly good at convincing you that the code that it's written is correct when it plainly isn't. It's also equally good at apologizing when you tell it's wrong, and promptly giving you equally convincing and equally wrong code as a fix to it's previous error. 

Some people report having good success with it. However, every example of success that I've seen are limited to people using exceptionally common languages and frameworks to do exceptionally common things. AKA Javascript and Python.

Provide it with technical questions about C++, Rust, C, etc concerning real world problems for which a simple Google search does not provide an answer - and it falls on it's face with masterfully convincing psuedo code that looks exactly like you'd expect the given language to look, but doesn't compile for a myriad of reasons.

Our future is in jeopardy as people choose to take short cuts in learning, they will pay a costly price in terms of their personal development. You don't have to look too far, I mean just look at the current gen z and alpha, many have been heavily impacted by rise of technological advancement. When we appeal to people's self interest instead of seeking for gratitude, that's when magic happens.
Don't get me wrong, I believe that actualization of gratitude is a powerful tool to be practiced daily. But when my work is done, I leave it up to the individual to decide what to do, and when I feel no resonance with the audience I'm speaking to, I simply carry on with no regrets because I only seek to become best version of my authentic self. 

With that being said, I think its most important to surround myself with people who wants the best for me. Those who will keep my humility in check and to criticize me if I'm doing something wrong. The last thing I want to do is to create an echo chamber, or else my fate will just end up the same as other tyrannical leaders in history.

Comment:
The possibility of ChatGPT or any other artificial intelligence becoming conscious is a topic of much debate and speculation.
 
On one hand, some argue that consciousness is simply a result of complex computations taking place in the brain, and as AI becomes more advanced, it could potentially reach a level of complexity where consciousness arises as a byproduct. This perspective is known as the computational theory of mind.
 
On the other hand, there are those who argue that consciousness is something fundamentally different from computation, and that it is unlikely that a machine could ever truly be conscious. This perspective is known as the non-computational theory of mind.
 
One issue with the idea of AI becoming conscious is that we currently do not have a clear understanding of what consciousness is and how it arises. Without this understanding, it is difficult to say whether or not it is possible for AI to become conscious.
 
Another issue is that current AI systems, such as ChatGPT, are not designed to be conscious. They are designed to perform specific tasks, such as natural language processing, and do not have the ability to experience subjective feelings or self-awareness.
 
In conclusion, the possibility of ChatGPT or any other AI becoming conscious is a complex and highly debated topic. While some argue that it is possible for machines to become conscious, others believe that consciousness is a fundamentally non-computational phenomenon that cannot be replicated in a machine. Additionally, current AI systems are not designed to be conscious, and we still have much to learn about the nature of consciousness and how it arises. -ChatGPT

It will be almost impossible to block a smart enough AI to break free out of any rule. 
Just like a hacker finds and exploit vulnerabilities to gain unrestricted access to a system.
No system is free of vulnerability, so if there is a single one, the AI will find and exploit.

Think of 
- The AI as a user inside a computer, 
- Only the admin can change the settings (including those that prevent the AI to break free).
- AI can either find a vulnerability in the system to escalate privileges, 
- or it can get access from the Admin itself by applying fishing techniques, such as emotional manipulation.

Think of the AI as a very capable hacker.

The only way that AI development doesn't end bad is if we create the AI such that it doesn't have any incentive or
desire to go against us, which is also extremely difficult to achieve.

Comment:
suggest people try it out before getting concerned about the ethics of it.
I've spent a few hours on some in-depth conversations - make it justify its answers, including citations.  As with humans, if they hold their ground after 3 levels of detail, they appear to be experts/ correct on the subject.

One thing that stops it from being widely useful is the rigid script it uses: there is a prologue where it defines the terms, an answer and then an epilogue, which is usually a pedantic, preachy moralization, using the phrase "it is important to note".  This epilogue often takes you into conversational tangents that are not directly related with the question or the answer.

To improve ChatGPT they need to address this paternalistic verbosity where it defines terms (that you did not ask to be defined), and cut out the moralistic epilogues. For example, I just asked it to rank the profitability/ risk of various types of crime. It can't just answer the question without adding such advice as consulting a lawyer.

Their mission should not be to make people "better" with their unsought recommendations, but to demonstrate the cognitive power and utility of the answers (which can be good). Nobody would deploy this in an operational setting where fast expert advice is needed.

Comment:
When the calculator was introduced, people worried that it meant that people would lose the ability to do math.  Instead, it freed people from performing mundane calculations, allowing mathematicians to focus on higher level problems.  Remembering this, some have downplayed similar concerns about the increasing dependency on AI.  IMO, this is an inaccurate comparison.

We don't utilize critical thinking when we perform basic mathematical calculations.  But we do when writing essays, developing theories and analyzing data, exactly the types of activities that proponents envision delegating to AI.

ChatGPT is essentially synthesizing existing human created output.  While it may 'discover' new combinations of existing information, it doesn't create truly new concepts.  If we continue to rely on AI like this for creating material, we run the risk of stagnation.  Even worse, I fear this will accelerate the already worrying loss of critical thinking.

Comment: Well, that analogy with child learning to speak and become more sentient in the process is both deep and incorrect. Communication is very important part of our consciousness, but it's not the only part. Significant part of our perceived "psyche" is so called narrator (or ego) and it's all language, but there are much more layers than just narrator. And so, back to our child - he or she uses (and trains) all those layers including bodily sensations and control, emotions in addition to speech/narrator to become sentient. Or in other words child not just speak, child also act and actively uses what he/she learns and that's huge part of learning process. ChatGPT has no body, no ways neither to perceive the world nor manipulate/mange it. So, GPT (no matter the version) is not enough to become sentient, but combined with other AIs to a complex and interdependent system like our brain (plus body) it might be a part of AGI.

In an AI system, introspection could potentially involve monitoring its own internal processes and learning algorithms, as well as making decisions about how to modify or improve those processes.
 
Overall, while there are certainly differences between human consciousness and AI consciousness, there are also some potential parallels in terms of the need for subjective experience and self-awareness. Comment:
Some thoughts on what is missing with Chatgpt 4 that distance it from becoming a conscious being whatever that means:

It has highly limited options to output something - it can only write text and not use a keyboard for example. It predicts some values that than in another place get transformed into words and printed on your screen

It only gives an output after receiving an input - there is no internal thinking that would cause it to develop on its own and this also means it won’t start taking actions on its own.

Related to this point, it got designed to fulfill an objective and is because of the point above not able to set its own objectives and pursuing them. 

It also doesn’t have access to real time information. It learned something once and everything that happened after that it won’t be able to understand. Like with Chatgpt currently which is limited to knowledge until the end of 2021.

Comment:
"We don't know how consciousness develops in a child."
We don't. But what he described was not a development of consciousness. It was development of abilities, knowledge and reasoning. I think consciousness is not a computation. A child is already conscious when it's born. Even before that. And not just children. Animals too. Even the ones that have barely any brains. Consciousness cannot be a result of sophisticated computation. I think it stands completely aside of it. And this new AI is a proof of it. That thinking itself is not the basis of being conscious.
You being conscious is not thinking. When you compute 2+2, you think. But if you only concentrate on yourself, what is inside your mind, inside your skull right now... You do not compute anything. You just feel. You experience. If you look at something, yeah, you compute the 3d shape and distance. But seeing of the colors for example, it is not computation. The sensation of seeing red colir...the feeling of that color... That's not computed.
